    "summary": "Bump.sh exposes two REST APIs (public Portal API and authenticated Workspace API), public documentation MCP servers at hub/doc URLs ending in `/mcp`, and the `bump` CLI.",
    "description": "Bump.sh is a platform for publishing API documentation from OpenAPI and AsyncAPI definitions and for generating managed MCP servers from workflow specifications. It provides hosted developer portals, changelogs, validation/diff tooling, and agent-facing MCP access.",
    "credentials": {
      "workspace_token": {
        "type": "api_key",
        "label": "Workspace API token",
        "generateUrl": "https://developers.bump.sh/doc/workspace/authentication",
        "setup": "In your Bump.sh documentation settings, generate or copy the access token for that documentation, then use it against the Workspace API. The auth guide says to use the token from your documentation settings; send it as `Authorization: Token <token>` or, deprecated, as HTTP Basic auth with no password. See [Workspace API authentication](https://developers.bump.sh/doc/workspace/authentication) and the [CLI help](https://docs.bump.sh/help/continuous-integration/cli/)."
      },
      "mcp_oauth": {
        "type": "oauth2",
        "label": "Bump.sh MCP OAuth client",
        "generateUrl": "https://bump.sh/oauth/registration",
        "setup": "For private Bump.sh MCP servers that use Bump.sh-managed auth, register an OAuth client via [dynamic client registration](https://bump.sh/oauth/registration), then have your MCP client complete OAuth against [authorize](https://bump.sh/oauth/authorize) and [token](https://bump.sh/oauth/token). Automated probes detected the available scopes `openid` and `mcp`. Bump.sh's MCP help says private MCP servers can require OAuth when users add the server to their AI tool. See [MCP access management](https://docs.bump.sh/help/mcp-servers/access-management/) and [using an MCP server](https://docs.bump.sh/help/mcp-servers/use-mcp-server/)."
      }
